69 (D) Home health aide services.
70 (4)(5) 'License' means a license issued by the department.
71 (5)(6) 'Licensee' means the individual, corporation, or public entity with whom rests the
72 ultimate responsibility for maintaining approved standards for the home health agency.
73 (6)(7) 'Parent home health agency' means the agency that develops and maintains
74 administrative controls of subunits or branch offices.
75 (7)(8) 'Physician' means an individual currently licensed or authorized to practice
76 medicine, surgery, or osteopathy in this state.
77 (9) 'Physician assistant' means an individual licensed pursuant to Article 4 of Chapter 34
78 of Title 43 and acting pursuant to the authority of Code Section 43-34-103.
79 (8)(10) 'Plan of treatment' means a plan written, signed, and reviewed at least every two
80 months by the patient's physician or a physician assistant acting pursuant to the authority
81 of Code Section 43-34-103 prescribing items and services for the patient's condition.
82 (9)(11) 'Registered nurse' means an individual who is currently licensed as a registered
83 professional nurse in this state.
84 (10)(12) 'Subunit' means a semiautonomous organization which serves patients in a
85 geographic area different from that of the parent agency and which, by virtue of the
86 distance between it and the parent agency, is judged incapable of sharing administration,
87 supervision, and services on a daily basis with the parent agency and must shall,
88 therefore, independently meet the licensing requirements for a home health agency and
89 shall be separately licensed."
90 SECTION 4.
91 Said title is further amended by revising Code Section 31-7-153, relating to standards for
92 patient care and agency operation, regulations as to issuance, denial, suspension, or
93 revocation of licenses, and hearings, as follows:
- 4 -

25 LC 52 0844S
94 "31-7-153.
95 The department shall promulgate regulations which define standards for the care, treatment,
96 health, safety, welfare, and comfort of patients served by home health agencies and for the
97 maintenance and operation of home health agencies which will promote safe and adequate
98 care and treatment of the patients. These regulations shall be no less stringent than those
99 required for participation of home health agencies in the Title XVIII medicare Medicare
100 program and shall include, but not be limited to, a provision requiring the agency to have
101 policies established by a professional group which includes at least one physician and one
102 registered nurse and appropriate representation from other professional disciplines;
103 provisions governing the services the agency provides; provisions for the supervision of
104 services by a physician, a physician assistant, or a registered nurse, as appropriate, and
105 maintenance of clinical records on all patients, including a plan of treatment prescribed by
106 a physician. The department is authorized to issue, deny, suspend, or revoke licenses in
107 accordance with regulations promulgated pursuant to this Code section. Such regulations
108 shall also include hearing procedures related to denial, suspension, or revocation of
109 licenses."
110 SECTION 5.
111 Said title is further amended by revising Code Section 31-7-154, relating to inspections, as
112 follows:
113 "31-7-154.
114 Each home health agency for which a license has been issued shall be periodically
115 inspected by an authorized representative of the department. Such inspections shall be for
116 the purpose of ensuring that this article is being followed. The department is directed to
117 ensure by inspection that the licensee is providing quality care to its patients in accordance
118 with the orders of the patient's physician or a physician assistant; provided, however, that
